ter of sovereignty to destabilize disembodied narratives of liberalism and progress and to raise questions about recognition, repair, and accountability. In tying theories of politics, colonialism, race, and affect together with Jamaica's history, Thomas presents a robust framework for understanding what it means to be human in the plantation's wake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aCivil rightszJamaicaxHistory. 0aPolitical violencezJamaicaxHistory. 0aRastafari movementzJamaica. 0aSocial justicezJamaicaxHistory. 0aSovereignty. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478007449zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478007449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478007449.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles